00:00:12.180 --> 00:00:14.970
- I've grown two different
plants of rhubarb

00:00:14.970 --> 00:00:18.950
in two different places,
but they both died.

00:00:18.950 --> 00:00:21.120
What do I do?

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:23.790
Rhubarb does better in more
northern parts of the country,

00:00:23.790 --> 00:00:25.110
where it's colder.

00:00:25.110 --> 00:00:28.080
But it will grow here, if
it's given well-drained sites.

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:29.850
So if you've got a
sandy soil or a raised

00:00:29.850 --> 00:00:32.790
bed with enough organic
matter so it doesn't dry out,

00:00:32.790 --> 00:00:34.529
you can grow rhubarb here.

00:00:34.529 --> 00:00:36.570
But the important thing
is don't keep it too wet,

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:37.680
especially when it's dormant.

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:38.370
Or it will rot.

00:00:38.370 --> 00:00:40.170
And that's probably
what happened to yours.

00:00:40.170 --> 00:00:42.640
If it's in a clay soil, it's
very likely to rot, as well.

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:45.600
So a sandy, well-drained soil is
your best bet to make it grow.

00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:49.400
